# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: soc2-compliance
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:soc2-compliance/american-institute-of-certified-public-accountants] The **American Institute of Certified Public Accountants** (**AICPA**) is the national professional organization of Certified Public Accountants (CPAs) in the United States, with more than 428,000 members in 130 countries.
[src:soc2-compliance/american-institute-of-certified-public-accountants] Founded in 1887 as the **American Association of Public Accountants** (**AAPA**), the organization sets ethical standards and U.S. auditing standards.
[src:soc2-compliance/american-institute-of-certified-public-accountants] It also develops and grades the Uniform CPA Examination.
[src:soc2-compliance/american-institute-of-certified-public-accountants] AICPA is headquartered in Durham, North Carolina, and maintains additional offices in New York City, Washington, D.C., and Ewing, New Jersey.
[src:soc2-compliance/american-institute-of-certified-public-accountants] AICPA and its predecessors date back to 1887, when the *American Association of Public Accountants* (AAPA) was formed.
[src:soc2-compliance/american-institute-of-certified-public-accountants] The Association went through several name changes over the years: the Institute of Public Accountants (1916), the American Institute of Accountants (1917), and the American Society of Public Accountants (1921), which merged into the American Institute of Accountants in 1936.
[src:soc2-compliance/american-institute-of-certified-public-accountants] At that time, the decision was made to restrict future membership to CPAs.
[src:soc2-compliance/american-institute-of-certified-public-accountants] The number of committees grew continually over the years.
[src:soc2-compliance/american-institute-of-certified-public-accountants] In 1999, the nearly 120 existing committees underwent a re-organization with approximately half of the standing committees being replaced with a volunteer group model that placed an increased emphasis on the use of task forces.
[src:soc2-compliance/american-institute-of-certified-public-accountants] The increased use of task forces allowed for more targeted efforts with the task forces being given a specific assignment then disbanding upon completion of that assignment.
[src:soc2-compliance/american-institute-of-certified-public-accountants] In January 2012, the AICPA entered into a joint venture with their equivalent in the UK, the Chartered Institute of Management Accountants (CIMA), a partnership that produced the Chartered Global Management Accountant (CGMA) designation.
[src:soc2-compliance/american-institute-of-certified-public-accountants] In 2014, the AICPA and the CIMA co-created the Global Management Accounting Principles (GMAPs).
[src:soc2-compliance/american-institute-of-certified-public-accountants] The AICPA and CIMA membership bodies remain and provide all existing benefits to members.
[src:soc2-compliance/american-institute-of-certified-public-accountants] In August 2019, the AICPA proposed a new standard to give auditors more guidance on auditing accounting estimates.
[src:soc2-compliance/american-institute-of-certified-public-accountants] 122, Section 540, *Auditing Accounting Estimates, Including Fair Value Accounting Estimates, and Related Disclosures.* It also amended a few other sections of the AICPA Professional Standards.
[src:soc2-compliance/american-institute-of-certified-public-accountants] The Uniform CPA Examination must be taken and passed by all those who wish to be licensed as a CPA.
[src:soc2-compliance/american-institute-of-certified-public-accountants] The exam is developed and scored by the Board of Examiners (BOE), a committee that consists of CPAs, state board regulators, psychometricians, and educators.
[src:soc2-compliance/american-institute-of-certified-public-accountants] AICPA sets generally accepted professional and technical standards for CPAs in multiple areas.
[src:soc2-compliance/american-institute-of-certified-public-accountants] Until the 1970s, the AICPA held a virtual monopoly in this field.
[src:soc2-compliance/american-institute-of-certified-public-accountants] In the 1970s, however, it transferred its responsibility for setting generally accepted accounting principles (GAAP) to the newly formed Financial Accounting Standards Board (FASB).
[src:soc2-compliance/american-institute-of-certified-public-accountants] Following this, it retained its standards setting function in areas such as financial statement auditing, professional ethics, attest services, CPA firm quality control, CPA tax practice, business valuation, and financial planning practice.
[src:soc2-compliance/american-institute-of-certified-public-accountants] Before passage of the Sarbanes-Oxley law, AICPA standards in these areas were considered "generally accepted" for all CPA practitioners.
[src:soc2-compliance/american-institute-of-certified-public-accountants] In the early 2000s, in response to events such as Enron's announcement that its financial statements couldn't be relied on and WorldCom's bankruptcy filing, Congress passed the Sarbanes-Oxley Act of 2002 (SOX).
[src:soc2-compliance/american-institute-of-certified-public-accountants] AICPA offers credentialing programs in certain subject areas for its members.
[src:soc2-compliance/american-institute-of-certified-public-accountants] The credentials are similar to state board certifications for attorneys, which also recognize subject matter-specific expertise.
[src:soc2-compliance/american-institute-of-certified-public-accountants] Aong with CIMA, AICPA issues the Chartered Global Management Accountant (CGMA) designation, which was established in 2012.
[src:soc2-compliance/american-institute-of-certified-public-accountants] Based on global quality standards for ethics and performance, CGMA designees are considered experts with credibility of advanced proficiency in finance, operations, strategy and management.
[src:soc2-compliance/american-institute-of-certified-public-accountants] The institute offers a number of scholarships for high school students, undergraduate, and graduate students, and working professionals.
[src:soc2-compliance/american-institute-of-certified-public-accountants] AICPA also runs public interest programs, including the Feed the Pig campaign and the 360 Degrees of Financial Literacy site.
[src:soc2-compliance/american-institute-of-certified-public-accountants] Feed the Pig, a national public service campaign sponsored by the AICPA and the Ad Council, provides personal finance resources for young Americans.
[src:soc2-compliance/american-institute-of-certified-public-accountants] 360 Degrees of Financial Literacy is a national volunteer effort of the nation's CPAs to help Americans understand their personal finances and develop money management skills.
[src:soc2-compliance/american-institute-of-certified-public-accountants] In 2022, the AICPA and the National Association of State Boards Accountancy announced that a new Uniform CPA exam would be released in 2024 as part of the CPA Evolution initiative.
[src:soc2-compliance/american-institute-of-certified-public-accountants] The new exam is based on a “Core + Discipline” model and will include core testing in accounting, auditing, and tax, as well as three Discipline sections (candidates must select one to complete).
[src:soc2-compliance/american-institute-of-certified-public-accountants] In the face of deteriorating interest in the field the accounting field has been forced to address the problems that many minorities in the accounting field face.
[src:soc2-compliance/american-institute-of-certified-public-accountants] These hurdles present themselves as the cost of education, the strain of a 150-credit major during university, the extremely difficult CPA exam, or just hostile business practices, they all contribute to the larger problem of the incredibly high standards that come with being a certified accountant.
[src:soc2-compliance/american-institute-of-certified-public-accountants] However, the AICPA has made strides, along with other organizations, to ensure diversity and equality within the field.
[src:soc2-compliance/american-institute-of-certified-public-accountants] Minorities and gender representation within the field of accounting have been a problem, with many efforts made to confront the looming problem.
[src:soc2-compliance/american-institute-of-certified-public-accountants] When looking at the number of registered CPAs in 1969, minorities made up 15% of all accountants.
[src:soc2-compliance/american-institute-of-certified-public-accountants] A lot of the reasons for such statistics are the numerous barriers that people of color have to face in order to even meet the qualifications to take the CPA exam.
[src:soc2-compliance/american-institute-of-certified-public-accountants] Even looking at the holistic picture of all college students enrolled in a Bachelor’s degree in the accounting program has steadily been decreasing since 2007.
[src:soc2-compliance/american-institute-of-certified-public-accountants] With the number of accountants needed in the growing job market, and interest in the profession dwindling, supporting accessibility to the career is essential.
[src:soc2-compliance/american-institute-of-certified-public-accountants] Specifically, the biggest barriers present would be the cost of education, as well as past efforts to refuse to acknowledge the credentials of those of said minorities, and denying them offers of employment.
[src:soc2-compliance/american-institute-of-certified-public-accountants] The role of the difficulty of education is highlighted in studies done by the AICPA and the National Association of State Boards of Accountancy (NASBA) themselves.
[src:soc2-compliance/american-institute-of-certified-public-accountants] One of the first actions taken by the AICPA was the creation of the Minority Recruitment and Equal Opportunity Committee, renamed the Minority Initiatives Committee (MIC) in 1969 .
[src:soc2-compliance/american-institute-of-certified-public-accountants] The main goals of this committee were to promote small minority owned businesses, while also providing opportunities for minority men and women.
[src:soc2-compliance/american-institute-of-certified-public-accountants] Additionally, the AICPA also invests in working with schools by forming programs that allow for a pipeline directly from university to real-world accounting jobs through minority based schools, such as the historically black colleges and universities (HBCUs).
[src:soc2-compliance/american-institute-of-certified-public-accountants] These programs existed not only to help students navigate the complex and wide world of accounting inside and outside of a university environment, but also to ease the financial burden that the 150-credit major imposed.
[src:soc2-compliance/american-institute-of-certified-public-accountants] These programs not only give strong mentoring opportunities but also give scholarships to help advance a select few promising students.
[src:soc2-compliance/american-institute-of-certified-public-accountants] As of 2013, the AICPA has been running the AICPA Scholarship for Minority Accounting Students for 40 years, which has provided over $14,600,000 in scholarships to over 8,000 students.
[src:soc2-compliance/american-institute-of-certified-public-accountants] Even the newly appointed vice-chair of the AICPA, Carla McCall, advocated for progress in diversity efforts and spearheads this sentiment with her own program in the AAFCPA’s Women’s Opportunity Network .
[src:soc2-compliance/american-institute-of-certified-public-accountants] WebTrust is a family of e-commerce assurance and auditing programs co-developed by the AICPA with the Canadian Institute of Chartered Accountants (CICA).
[src:soc2-compliance/american-institute-of-certified-public-accountants] Accounting associations in the UK, Australia, New Zealand and Hong Kong also participate in the program.
[src:soc2-compliance/american-institute-of-certified-public-accountants] A specialized variant of the program exists for certificate authorities.
[src:soc2-compliance/american-institute-of-certified-public-accountants] The AICPA is a leading member of the International Federation of Accountants and the Global Accounting Alliance, and the Tax Professionals United for Taxpayer Relief Coalition.
[src:soc2-compliance/american-institute-of-certified-public-accountants] The AICPA is an affiliate of the Institute of Chartered Accountants of the Caribbean.
[src:soc2-compliance/american-institute-of-certified-public-accountants] Members of the AICPA must attest annually to meeting the requirements for their membership types, complying with the AICPA's bylaws and upholding the AICPA's Code of Profession Conduct.
[src:soc2-compliance/american-institute-of-certified-public-accountants] Members are subject to audit and, if found to be non-compliant, may be expelled from the AICPA.
[src:soc2-compliance/american-institute-of-certified-public-accountants] Since Q3 of 2018, AICPA has been publishing the personal financial satisfaction index on a quarterly basis that indicates the general understanding of economic factors affecting the financial standing of a typical American.
[src:soc2-compliance/american-institute-of-certified-public-accountants] As the COVID-19 pandemic has strained the U.S. economy and put millions out of work, Americans have experienced the biggest drop in their personal financial satisfaction in more than a decade.
[src:soc2-compliance/american-institute-of-certified-public-accountants] The AICPA's Q1 2020 Personal Financial Satisfaction index (PFSi) measures 32.9, a 20 percent (8.29 point) decrease from the previous quarter.
[src:soc2-compliance/american-institute-of-certified-public-accountants] This is the largest quarterly drop the PFSi has experienced since the Great Recession (Q4 2009).
[src:soc2-compliance/audit-trail] An **audit trail** (also called **audit log**) is a security-relevant chronological record, set of records, and/or destination and source of records that provide documentary evidence of the sequence of activities that have affected at any time a specific operation, procedure, event, or device.
[src:soc2-compliance/audit-trail] Audit records typically result from activities such as financial transactions, scientific research and health care data transactions, or communications by individual people, systems, accounts, or other entities.
[src:soc2-compliance/audit-trail] The process that creates an audit trail is typically required to always run in a privileged mode, so it can access and supervise all actions from all users; a normal user should not be allowed to stop/change it.
[src:soc2-compliance/audit-trail] Furthermore, for the same reason, the trail file or database table with a trail should not be accessible to normal users.
[src:soc2-compliance/audit-trail] Another way of handling this issue is through the use of a role-based security model in the software.
[src:soc2-compliance/audit-trail] The software can operate with the closed-looped controls, or as a 'closed system', as required by many companies when using audit trail functionality.
[src:soc2-compliance/audit-trail] In telecommunications, the term means a record of both completed and attempted accesses and service, or data forming a logical path linking a sequence of events, used to trace the transactions that have affected the contents of a record.
[src:soc2-compliance/audit-trail] In information or communications security, information audit means a chronological record of system activities to enable the reconstruction and examination of the sequence of events and/or changes in an event.
[src:soc2-compliance/audit-trail] Information put away or transmitted in paired structure that might be depended upon in court.
[src:soc2-compliance/audit-trail] An audit trail is a progression of records of computer data about a working framework, an application, or client exercises.
[src:soc2-compliance/audit-trail] Computer frameworks may have a few audit trails each gave to a specific sort of action.
[src:soc2-compliance/audit-trail] Related to proper apparatuses and systems, audit trails can help with distinguishing security infringement, execution issues and application issues.
[src:soc2-compliance/audit-trail] Routine log audits and investigation are valuable for distinguishing security episodes, approach infringement, fake movement, and operational issues soon after they have happened, and for giving information valuable to settling such issues.
[src:soc2-compliance/audit-trail] Audit logs can likewise be valuable for performing forensic investigation, supporting the associations inside examinations, setting up baselines, and distinguishing operational patterns and long run issues.
[src:soc2-compliance/audit-trail] In nursing research, it refers to the act of maintaining a running log or journal of decisions relating to a research project, thus making clear the steps taken and changes made to the original protocol.
[src:soc2-compliance/audit-trail] In accounting, it refers to documentation of detailed transactions supporting summary ledger entries.
[src:soc2-compliance/audit-trail] This documentation may be on paper or on electronic records.
[src:soc2-compliance/audit-trail] In online proofing, it pertains to the version history of a piece of artwork, design, photograph, video, or web design proof in a project.
[src:soc2-compliance/audit-trail] In clinical research, server based systems such as clinical trial management systems (CTMS) require audit trails.
[src:soc2-compliance/audit-trail] Anything regulatory or QA/QC related also requires audit trails.
[src:soc2-compliance/audit-trail] In pharmaceutical manufacturing, it is a Good Manufacturing Practice regulatory requirement software generate audit trails, but not all software have audit trail functionality built-in.
[src:soc2-compliance/audit-trail] The first 'generic' audit trail generating software came out late 2021.
[src:soc2-compliance/audit-trail] The software is called Audit Trail Control, capable of fulfilling regulatory requirements for any software used in pharmaceutical manufacturing.
[src:soc2-compliance/audit-trail] In voting, a voter-verified paper audit trail is a method of providing feedback to voters using a ballotless voting system.
[src:soc2-compliance/audit-trail] In employment and human resources contexts, audit trails provide a documented record of investigative steps taken, including complaint intake, witness interviews, and remedial actions taken, specifically in cases involving allegations of misconduct, discrimination or harassment.
[src:soc2-compliance/audit-trail] Equal Employment Opportunity Commission (EEOC), employers are required to conduct a "prompt and adequate investigation" and take "appropriate action based on the findings," making a reviewable audit trail central to demonstrating compliance.
[src:soc2-compliance/audit-trail] Multiple regulatory frameworks require organizations to maintain audit trails for compliance purposes.
[src:soc2-compliance/audit-trail] The HIPAA Security Rule requires covered entities and business associates to implement hardware, software, and procedural mechanisms that record and examine activity in information systems containing electronic protected health information (ePHI).
[src:soc2-compliance/audit-trail] These audit controls, specified under the technical safeguards at 45 CFR 164.312(b), must capture information such as user logins, file accesses, and modifications to ePHI.
[src:soc2-compliance/audit-trail] A proposed update to the HIPAA Security Rule (NPRM, December 2024) would require covered entities to review audit logs at least once every 30 days to detect unauthorized access or other security incidents.
[src:soc2-compliance/audit-trail] The Sarbanes-Oxley Act (SOX) requires publicly traded companies to maintain adequate internal controls over financial reporting, which in practice necessitates comprehensive audit trails for financial transactions and system access.
[src:soc2-compliance/audit-trail] The Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS) Requirement 10 mandates that organizations track and monitor all access to network resources and cardholder data through logging mechanisms.
[src:soc2-compliance/governance-risk-management-and-compliance] COSO updated their standards accordingly.
[src:soc2-compliance/governance-risk-management-and-compliance] As companies began efforts to comply with these regulations, the interconnectedness of governance, risk management, and compliance became clear.
[src:soc2-compliance/governance-risk-management-and-compliance] This created a market for training and software to bring these function together; for example, in 2002, Symbiant, a UK software development company, created the first GRC software that let teams work together online, combining risk registers, evaluations and audit tracking all in one system.
[src:soc2-compliance/governance-risk-management-and-compliance] The term "Governance, risk, and compliance" or "GRC" was published by Scott Mitchell, founder of the Open Compliance and Ethics Group (OCEG), in an academic paper in 2007.
[src:soc2-compliance/governance-risk-management-and-compliance] Governance, risk, and compliance (GRC) are three related facets that aim to assure an organization reliably achieves objectives, addresses uncertainty and acts with integrity.
[src:soc2-compliance/governance-risk-management-and-compliance] Governance, risk and compliance (GRC) is a discipline that aims to synchronize information and activity across governance, and compliance in order to operate more efficiently, enable effective information sharing, more effectively report activities and avoid wasteful overlaps.
[src:soc2-compliance/governance-risk-management-and-compliance] If not integrated and instead tackled in a traditional "silo" approach, most organizations must sustain unmanageable numbers of GRC-related requirements due to changes in technology, increasing data storage, market globalization and increased regulation.
[src:soc2-compliance/governance-risk-management-and-compliance] Specific fields have developed GRC approaches; there is financial GRC (aka FinGRC), Legal GRC, and Operational GRC.
[src:soc2-compliance/governance-risk-management-and-compliance] As companies have begun to adopt artificial intelligence to help run their businesses, the risks intrinsic to AI raise GRC challenges to the companies using AI products.
[src:soc2-compliance/governance-risk-management-and-compliance] As of 2025, some companies were beginning to adopt AI tools to help them manage GRC.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] An **information security audit** is an audit of the level of information security in an organization.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] It is an independent review and examination of system records, activities, and related documents.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] These audits are intended to improve the level of information security, avoid improper information security designs, and optimize the efficiency of the security safeguards and security processes.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] Within the broad scope of auditing information security there are multiple types of audits, multiple objectives for different audits, etc.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] Most commonly the controls being audited can be categorized as technical, physical and administrative.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] Auditing information security covers topics from auditing the physical security of data centers to auditing the logical security of databases, and highlights key components to look for and different methods for auditing these areas.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] When centered on the Information technology (IT) aspects of information security, it can be seen as a part of an information technology audit.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] It is often then referred to as an information technology security audit or a computer security audit.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] However, information security encompasses much more than IT.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] The auditor is responsible for assessing the current technological maturity level of a company during the first stage of the audit.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] This stage is used to assess the current status of the company and helps identify the required time, cost and scope of an audit.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] The auditor should plan a company's audit based on the information found in the previous step.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] Planning an audit helps the auditor obtain sufficient and appropriate evidence for each company's specific circumstances.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] It helps predict audit costs at a reasonable level, assign the proper manpower and time line and avoid misunderstandings with clients.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] An auditor should be adequately educated about the company and its critical business activities before conducting a data center review.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] The objective of the data center is to align data center activities with the goals of the business while maintaining the security and integrity of critical information and processes.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] In the next step, the auditor outlines the objectives of the audit after that conducting a review of a corporate data center takes place.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] Auditors consider multiple factors that relate to data center procedures and activities that potentially identify audit risks in the operating environment and assess the controls in place that mitigate those risks.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] After thorough testing and analysis, the auditor is able to adequately determine if the data center maintains proper controls and is operating efficiently and effectively.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] The next step is to collect evidence to satisfy data center audit objectives.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] This involves traveling to the data center location and observing processes within the data center.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] After the audit examination is completed, the audit findings and suggestions for corrective actions can be communicated to responsible stakeholders in a formal meeting.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] This ensures better understanding and support of the audit recommendations.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] It also gives the audited organization an opportunity to express its views on the issues raised.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] Writing a report after such a meeting and describing where agreements have been reached on all audit issues can greatly enhance audit effectiveness.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] Exit conferences also help finalize recommendations that are practical and feasible.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] The data center review report should summarize the auditor's findings and be similar in format to a standard review report.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] The review report should be dated as of the completion of the auditor's inquiry and procedures.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] It should state what the review entailed and explain that a review provides only "limited assurance" to third parties.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] Typically, a data center review report consolidates the entirety of the audit.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] It also offers recommendations surrounding proper implementation of physical safeguards and advises the client on appropriate roles and responsibilities of its personnel.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] The report may optionally include rankings of the security vulnerabilities identified throughout the performance of the audit and the urgency of the tasks necessary to address them.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] Rankings like "high", "low", and "medium" can be used to describe the imperativeness of the tasks.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] In certain regulated industries, information security audits may be mandated by law.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] The Office for Civil Rights (OCR) within HHS enforces these requirements and has cited the failure to conduct an adequate risk analysis as one of the most common findings in HIPAA enforcement actions.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] To assist organizations in meeting these requirements, the Office of the National Coordinator for Health Information Technology (ONC) and OCR developed a free Security Risk Assessment Tool for small and medium-sized healthcare practices.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] Information Security Officer (ISO) is a relatively new position, which has emerged in organizations to deal in the aftermath of chaotic growth in information technology and network communication.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] The role of the ISO has been very nebulous since the problem that they were created to address was not defined clearly.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] The role of an ISO has become one of following the dynamics of the security environment and keeping the risk posture balanced for the organization.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] Information systems audits combine the efforts and skill sets from the accounting and technology fields.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] Professionals from both fields rely on one another to ensure the security of the information and data.With this collaboration, the security of the information system has proven to increase over time.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] In relation to the information systems audit, the role of the auditor is to examine the company's controls of the security program.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] Furthermore, the auditor discloses the operating effectiveness of these controls in an audit report.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] The Information Systems Audit and Control Association (ISACA), an Information Technology professional organization, promotes gaining expertise through various certifications.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] The benefits of these certifications are applicable to external and internal personnel of the system.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] The auditor should ask certain questions to better understand the network and its vulnerabilities.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] The auditor should first assess the extent of the network is and how it is structured.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] A network diagram can assist the auditor in this process.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] The next question an auditor should ask is what critical information this network must protect.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] Things such as enterprise systems, mail servers, web servers, and host applications accessed by customers are typically areas of focus.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] It is also important to know who has access and to what parts.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] Do customers and vendors have access to systems on the network?
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] Can employees access information from home?
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] Lastly, the auditor should assess how the network is connected to external networks and how it is protected.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] Most networks are at least connected to the internet, which could be a point of vulnerability.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] These are critical questions in protecting networks.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] When you have a function that deals with money either incoming or outgoing it is very important to make sure that duties are segregated to minimize and hopefully prevent fraud.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] One of the key ways to ensure proper segregation of duties (SoD) from a systems perspective is to review individuals' access authorizations.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] For complex systems such as SAP, it is often preferred to use tools developed specifically to assess and analyze SoD conflicts and other types of system activity.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] For other systems or for multiple system formats you should monitor which users may have superuser access to the system giving them unlimited access to all aspects of the system.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] Also, developing a matrix for all functions highlighting the points where proper segregation of duties has been breached will help identify potential material weaknesses by cross-checking each employee's available accesses.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] This is as important if not more so in the development function as it is in production.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] Ensuring that people who develop the programs are not the ones who are authorized to pull it into production is key to preventing unauthorized programs into the production environment where they can be used to perpetrate fraud.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] In assessing the need for a client to implement encryption policies for their organization, the Auditor should conduct an analysis of the client's risk and data value.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] Companies with multiple external users, e-commerce applications, and sensitive customer/employee information should maintain rigid encryption policies aimed at encrypting the correct data at the appropriate stage in the data collection process.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] Auditors should continually evaluate their client's encryption policies and procedures.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] Companies that are heavily reliant on e-commerce systems and wireless networks are extremely vulnerable to theft and loss of critical information in transmission.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] Policies and procedures should be documented and carried out to ensure that all transmitted data is protected.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] The auditor should verify that management has controls in place over the data encryption management process.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] Access to keys should require dual control, keys should be composed of two separate components and should be maintained on a computer that is not accessible to programmers or outside users.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] Furthermore, management should attest that encryption policies ensure data protection at the desired level and verify that the cost of encrypting the data does not exceed the value of the information itself.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] All data that is required to be maintained for an extensive amount of time should be encrypted and transported to a remote location.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] Procedures should be in place to guarantee that all encrypted sensitive information arrives at its location and is stored properly.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] Finally, the auditor should attain verification from management that the encryption system is strong, not attackable, and compliant with all local and international laws and regulations.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] Just as it sounds, a logical security audit follows a format in an organized procedure.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] The first step in an audit of any system is to seek to understand its components and its structure.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] When auditing logical security the auditor should investigate what security controls are in place, and how they work.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] Network security is achieved by various tools including firewalls and proxy servers, encryption, logical security and access controls, anti-virus software, and auditing systems such as log management.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] Firewalls are a very basic part of network security.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] They are often placed between the private local network and the internet.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] Firewalls provide a flow-through for traffic in which it can be authenticated, monitored, logged, and reported.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] Some different types of firewalls include network layer firewalls, screened subnet firewalls, packet filter firewalls, dynamic packet filtering firewalls, hybrid firewalls, transparent firewalls, and application-level firewalls.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] The process of encryption involves converting plain text into a series of unreadable characters known as the ciphertext.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] If the encrypted text is stolen or attained while in transit, the content is unreadable to the viewer.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] This guarantees secure transmission and is extremely useful to companies sending/receiving critical information.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] Once encrypted information arrives at its intended recipient, the decryption process is deployed to restore the ciphertext back to plaintext.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] Proxy servers hide the true address of the client workstation and can also act as a firewall.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] Proxy server firewalls have special software to enforce authentication.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] Proxy server firewalls act as a middle man for user requests.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] Antivirus software programs such as McAfee and Symantec software locate and dispose of malicious content.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] These virus protection programs run live updates to ensure they have the latest information about known computer viruses.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] Logical security includes software safeguards for an organization's systems, including user ID and password access, authentication, access rights and authority levels.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] These measures are to ensure that only authorized users are able to perform actions or access information in a network or a workstation.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] Vulnerabilities in an organization's IT systems are often not attributed to technical weaknesses, but rather related to individual behavior of employees within the organization.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] A simple example of this is users leaving their computers unlocked or being vulnerable to phishing attacks.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] As a result, a thorough InfoSec audit will frequently include a penetration test in which auditors attempt to gain access to as much of the system as possible, from both the perspective of a typical employee as well as an outsider.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] A behavioral audit ensures preventative measures are in place such as a phishing webinar, where employees are made aware of what phishing is and how to detect it.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] System and process assurance audits combine elements from IT infrastructure and application/information security audits and use diverse controls in categories such as Completeness, Accuracy, Validity (V) and Restricted access (CAVR).
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] When it comes to programming it is important to ensure proper physical and password protection exists around servers and mainframes for the development and update of key systems.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] Having physical access security at one's data center or office such as electronic badges and badge readers, security guards, choke points, and security cameras is vitally important to ensuring the security of applications and data.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] Then one needs to have security around changes to the system.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] Those usually have to do with proper security access to make the changes and having proper authorization procedures in place for pulling programming changes from development through test and finally into production.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] With processing, it is important that procedures and monitoring of a few different aspects such as the input of falsified or erroneous data, incomplete processing, duplicate transactions and untimely processing are in place.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] Making sure that input is randomly reviewed or that all processing has proper approval is a way to ensure this.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] It is important to be able to identify incomplete processing and ensure that proper procedures are in place for either completing it or deleting it from the system if it was in error.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] There should also be procedures to identify and correct duplicate entries.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] Finally, when it comes to processing that is not being done on a timely basis one should back-track the associated data to see where the delay is coming from and identify whether or not this delay creates any control concerns.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] Finally, access, it is important to realize that maintaining network security against unauthorized access is one of the major focuses for companies as threats can come from a few sources.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] First, one has internal unauthorized access.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] It is very important to have system access passwords that must be changed regularly and that there is a way to track access and changes so one is able to identify who made what changes.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] The second arena to be concerned with is remote access, people accessing one's system from the outside through the internet.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] Setting up firewalls and password protection to on-line data changes are key to protecting against unauthorized remote access.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] One way to identify weaknesses in access controls is to bring in a hacker to try and crack one's system by either gaining entry to the building and using an internal terminal or hacking in from the outside through remote access.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] An information security audit can be defined by examining the different aspects of information security.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] External and internal professionals within an institution have the responsibility of maintaining and inspecting the adequacy and effectiveness of information security.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] As in any institution, there are various controls to be implemented and maintained.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] To secure the information, an institution is expected to apply security measures to circumvent outside intervention.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] By and large, the two concepts of application security and segregation of duties are both in many ways connected, and they both have the same goal: to protect the integrity of the company's data and to prevent fraud.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] For application security, it has to do with preventing unauthorized access to hardware and software through having proper security measures both physical and electronic in place.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] With segregation of duties, it is primarily a physical review of individuals' access to the systems and processing and ensuring that there are no overlaps that could lead to fraud.
[src:soc2-compliance/information-security-audit] The type of audit the individual performs determines the specific procedures and tests to be executed throughout the audit process.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] It is a means by which an organization's resources are directed, monitored, and measured.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] It plays an important role in detecting and preventing fraud and protecting the organization's resources, both physical (e.g., machinery and property) and intangible (e.g., reputation or intellectual property such as trademarks).
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] At the organizational level, internal control objectives relate to the reliability of financial reporting, timely feedback on the achievement of operational or strategic goals, and compliance with laws and regulations.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] Internal control is a key element of the Foreign Corrupt Practices Act (FCPA) of 1977 and the Sarbanes–Oxley Act of 2002, which required improvements in internal control in United States public corporations.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] Internal controls within business entities are also referred to as **operational controls**.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] The main controls in place are sometimes referred to as "key financial controls" (KFCs).
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] Internal controls have existed from ancient times.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] In Hellenistic Egypt there was a dual administration, with one set of bureaucrats charged with collecting taxes and another with supervising them.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] In the Republic of China, the Supervising Authority (检察院; pinyin: Jiǎnchá Yùan), one of the five branches of government, is an investigatory agency that monitors the other branches of government.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] There are many definitions of internal control, as it affects the various constituencies (stakeholders) of an organization in various ways and at different levels of aggregation.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] Control Activities-the policies and procedures that help ensure management directives are carried out.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] Monitoring-processes used to assess the quality of internal control performance over time.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] The COSO definition relates to the aggregate control system of the organization, which is composed of many individual control procedures.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] Discrete control procedures, or *controls* are defined by the SEC as: "...a specific set of policies, procedures, and activities designed to meet an objective.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] A control may exist within a designated function or activity in a process.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] A control’s impact ... may be entity-wide or specific to an account balance, class of transactions or application.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] Controls have unique characteristics – for example, they can be: automated or manual; reconciliations; segregation of duties; review and approval authorizations; safeguarding and accountability of assets; preventing or detecting error or fraud.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] More generally, setting objectives, budgets, plans and other expectations establish criteria for control.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] Control itself exists to keep performance or a state of affairs within what is expected, allowed or accepted.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] Control built within a process is internal in nature.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] It takes place with a combination of interrelated components – such as social environment effecting behavior of employees, information necessary in control, and policies and procedures.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] Internal control structure is a plan determining how internal control consists of these elements.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] The concepts of corporate governance also heavily rely on the necessity of internal controls.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] Internal controls help ensure that processes operate as designed and that risk responses (risk treatments) in risk management are carried out (COSO II).
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] In addition, there needs to be in place circumstances ensuring that the aforementioned procedures will be performed as intended: right attitudes, integrity and competence, and monitoring by managers.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] According to the COSO Framework, everyone in an organization has responsibility for internal control to some extent.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] Virtually all employees produce information used in the internal control system or take other actions needed to affect control.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] Also, all personnel should be responsible for communicating upward problems in operations, non-compliance with the code of conduct, or other policy violations or illegal actions.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] The Chief Executive Officer (the top manager) of the organization has overall responsibility for designing and implementing effective internal control.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] More than any other individual, the chief executive sets the "tone at the top" that affects integrity and ethics and other factors of a positive control environment.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] In a large company, the chief executive fulfills this duty by providing leadership and direction to senior managers and reviewing the way they're controlling the business.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] Senior managers, in turn, assign responsibility for establishment of more specific internal control policies and procedures to personnel responsible for the unit's functions.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] In a smaller entity, the influence of the chief executive, often an owner-manager, is usually more direct.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] In any event, in a cascading responsibility, a manager is effectively a chief executive of his or her sphere of responsibility.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] Of particular significance are financial officers and their staffs, whose control activities cut across, as well as up and down, the operating and other units of an enterprise.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] Management is accountable to the board of directors, which provides governance, guidance and oversight.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] Effective board members are objective, capable and inquisitive.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] They also have a knowledge of the entity's activities and environment, and commit the time necessary to fulfil their board responsibilities.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] Management may be in a position to override controls and ignore or stifle communications from subordinates, enabling a dishonest management which intentionally misrepresents results to cover its tracks.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] A strong, active board, particularly when coupled with effective upward communications channels and capable financial, legal and internal audit functions, is often best able to identify and correct such a problem.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] The internal auditors and external auditors of the organization also measure the effectiveness of internal control through their efforts.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] They assess whether the controls are properly designed, implemented and working effectively, and make recommendations on how to improve internal control.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] They may also review Information technology controls, which relate to the IT systems of the organization.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] Review significant findings or unsatisfactory internal audit reports, or audit problems or difficulties encountered by the external independent auditor.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] Monitor the adequacy of the organization's internal controls and ensure that all fraud cases are acted upon.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] The audit committee also has a key role in selecting and recommending the appointment of the external auditor, and in approving any non-audit services provided by that auditor, to safeguard auditor independence.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] They also ensure that benefit-related performance measures are properly used by the management of the organization.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] All staff members should be responsible for reporting problems of operations, monitoring and improving their performance, and monitoring non-compliance with the corporate policies and various professional codes, or violations of policies, standards, practices and procedures.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] Their particular responsibilities should be documented in their individual personnel files.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] In performance management activities they take part in all compliance and performance data collection and processing activities as they are part of various organizational units and may also be responsible for various compliance and operational-related activities of the organization.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] Staff and junior managers may be involved in evaluating the controls within their own organizational unit using a control self-assessment.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] Advances in technology and data analysis have led to the development of numerous tools which can automatically evaluate the effectiveness of internal controls.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] Used in conjunction with continuous auditing, continuous controls monitoring provides assurance on financial information flowing through the business processes.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] There are laws and regulations on internal control related to financial reporting in a number of jurisdictions.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] In the U.S. these regulations are specifically established by Sections 404 and 302 of the Sarbanes-Oxley Act.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] Internal control can provide reasonable, not absolute, assurance that the objectives of an organization will be met.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] The concept of reasonable assurance implies a high degree of assurance, constrained by the costs and benefits of establishing incremental control procedures.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] Effective internal control implies the organization generates reliable financial reporting and substantially complies with the laws and regulations that apply to it.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] However, whether an organization achieves operational and strategic objectives may depend on factors outside the enterprise, such as competition or technological innovation.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] These factors are outside the scope of internal control; therefore, effective internal control provides only timely information or feedback on progress towards the achievement of operational and strategic objectives, but cannot guarantee their achievement.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] b) the nature of the control activity itself.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] Assertions are representations by the management embodied in the financial statements.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] Further such fixed assets must be disclosed and represented correctly in the financial statement according to the financial reporting framework applicable to the company.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] Controls may be defined against the particular financial statement assertion to which they relate.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] Existence/Occurrence/Validity: Only valid or authorized transactions are processed.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] Rights and obligations: Assets are the rights of the organization and the liabilities are its obligations as of a given date.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] Completeness: All transactions are processed that should be.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] Valuation: Transactions are valued accurately using the proper methodology, such as a specified means of computation or formula.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] Control activities may also be explained by the type or nature of activity.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] Control precision describes the alignment or correlation between a particular control procedure and a given control objective or risk.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] A control with direct impact on the achievement of an objective (or mitigation of a risk) is said to be more precise than one with indirect impact on the objective or risk.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] Precision is distinct from sufficiency; that is, multiple controls with varying degrees of precision may be involved in achieving a control objective or mitigating a risk.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] Precision is an important factor in performing a SOX 404 top-down risk assessment.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] After identifying specific financial reporting material misstatement risks, management and the external auditors are required to identify and test controls that mitigate the risks.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] This involves making judgments regarding both precision and sufficiency of controls required to mitigate the risks.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] Risks and controls may be entity-level or assertion-level under the PCAOB guidance.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] Entity-level controls are identified to address entity-level risks.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] However, a combination of entity-level and assertion-level controls are typically identified to address assertion-level risks.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] The PCAOB set forth a three-level hierarchy for considering the precision of entity-level controls.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] Later guidance by the PCAOB regarding small public firms provided several factors to consider in assessing precision.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] Internal control plays an important role in the prevention and detection of fraud.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] Under the Sarbanes-Oxley Act, companies are required to perform a fraud risk assessment and assess related controls.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] This typically involves identifying scenarios in which theft or loss could occur and determining if existing control procedures effectively manage the risk to an acceptable level.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] The risk that senior management might override important financial controls to manipulate financial reporting is also a key area of focus in fraud risk assessment.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] The AICPA, IIA, and ACFE also sponsored a guide published during 2008 that includes a framework for helping organizations manage their fraud risk.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] Controls can be evaluated and improved to make a business operation run more effectively and efficiently.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] For example, automating controls that are manual in nature can save costs and improve transaction processing.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] If the internal control system is thought of by executives as only a means of preventing fraud and complying with laws and regulations, an important opportunity may be missed.
[src:soc2-compliance/internal-control] Internal controls can also be used to systematically improve businesses, particularly in regard to effectiveness and efficiency.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] In general, **compliance** means conforming to a rule, such as a specification, policy, standard or law.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Compliance has traditionally been explained by reference to deterrence theory, according to which punishing a behavior will decrease the violations both by the wrongdoer (specific deterrence) and by others (general deterrence).
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] This view has been supported by economic theory, which has framed punishment in terms of costs and has explained compliance in terms of a cost-benefit equilibrium (Becker 1968).
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] However, psychological research on motivation provides an alternative view: granting rewards (Deci, Koestner and Ryan, 1999) or imposing fines (Gneezy Rustichini 2000) for a certain behavior is a form of extrinsic motivation that weakens intrinsic motivation and ultimately undermines compliance.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Regulations and accrediting organizations vary among fields, with examples such as PCI-DSS and GLBA in the financial industry, FISMA for U.S. federal agencies, HACCP for the food and beverage industry, and the Joint Commission and HIPAA in healthcare.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] In some cases other compliance frameworks (such as COBIT) or even standards (NIST) inform on how to comply with regulations.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Some organizations keep compliance data—all data belonging or pertaining to the enterprise or included in the law, which can be used for the purpose of implementing or validating compliance—in a separate store for meeting reporting requirements.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Compliance software is increasingly being implemented to help companies manage their compliance data more efficiently.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] This store may include calculations, data transfers, and audit trails.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] The ISO also produces international standards such as ISO/IEC 27002 to help organizations meet regulatory compliance with their security management and assurance best practices.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Some local or international specialized organizations such as the American Society of Mechanical Engineers (ASME) also develop standards and regulation codes.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] They thereby provide a wide range of rules and directives to ensure compliance of the products to safety, security or design standards.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Regulatory compliance varies not only by industry but often by location.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] The financial, research, and pharmaceutical regulatory structures in one country, for example, may be similar but with particularly different nuances in another country.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] These similarities and differences are often a product "of reactions to the changing objectives and requirements in different countries, industries, and policy contexts".
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] These regulators help to ensure financial institutes meet their promises, that transactional information is well documented, and that competition is fair while protecting consumers.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Australian organisations seeking to remain compliant with various regulations may turn to AS ISO 19600:2015 (which supersedes AS 3806-2006).
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] This standard helps organisations with compliance management, placing "emphasis on the organisational elements that are required to support compliance" while also recognizing the need for continual improvement.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] In Canada, federal regulation of deposits, insurance, and superannuation is governed by two independent bodies: the OSFI through the Bank Act, and FINTRAC, mandated by the Proceeds of Crime (Money Laundering) and Terrorist Financing Act, 2001 (PCMLTFA).
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] These groups protect consumers, regulate how risk is controlled and managed, and investigate illegal action such as money laundering and terrorist financing.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] On a provincial level, each province maintain individuals laws and agencies.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Unlike any other major federation, Canada does not have a securities regulatory authority at the federal government level.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] The provincial and territorial regulators work together to coordinate and harmonize regulation of the Canadian capital markets through the Canadian Securities Administrators (CSA).
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Other key regulators in Canada include the Canadian Food Inspection Agency (CFIA) for food safety, animal health, and plant health; Health Canada for public health; and Environment and Climate Change Canada for environment and sustainable energy.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] For more industry specific guidance, e.g., financial institutions, Canada's E-13 Regulatory Compliance Management provides specific compliance risk management tactics.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Regulatory compliance in the European Union (EU) is governed by a harmonized legal framework designed to ensure consistency across member states while allowing for national implementation.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] EU compliance regulations cover various industries, including consumer product safety, financial services, environmental protection, and data privacy.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] The General Product Safety Regulation (GPSR) establishes a unified safety framework for consumer products across the EU, requiring manufacturers to conduct risk assessments, maintain traceability documentation, and meet safety compliance standards before placing products on the market.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] The GPSR applies to all consumer products made available in the EU unless covered by sector-specific regulations, such as medical devices or food products.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] The regulation extends to products sold through e-commerce platforms, requiring online marketplaces to ensure that only compliant products are listed.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Fulfillment service providers are also included as economic operators, making them responsible for product safety compliance in certain cases.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] For business compliance, the EU’s regulatory approach is guided by the New Legislative Framework (NLF) and various sector-specific directives and regulations.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Businesses must comply with EU product conformity assessments and affix the CE marking to indicate compliance with essential safety and performance standards.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Financial compliance is enforced through regulations such as the Markets in Financial Instruments Directive (MiFID II) and the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), which set strict requirements for financial transparency, consumer protection, and data security.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] The EU Legislation Compliance framework ensures that organizations operate within the legal boundaries of EU directives, helping public and private entities manage regulatory risks efficiently.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Companies operating in the EU must stay updated on evolving compliance requirements, as non-compliance can lead to fines, product recalls, or restrictions on market access.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] The financial sector in the Netherlands is heavily regulated.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] The Dutch Central Bank (De Nederlandsche Bank N.V.) is the prudential regulator while the Netherlands Authority for Financial Markets (AFM) is the regulator for behavioral supervision of financial institutions and markets.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] In India, compliance regulation takes place across three strata: Central, State, and Local regulation.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] India veers towards central regulation, especially of financial organizations and foreign funds.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Compliance regulations vary based on the industry segment in addition to the geographical mix.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Most regulation comes in the following broad categories: economic regulation, regulation in the public interest, and environmental regulation.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] India has also been characterized by poor compliance - reports suggest that only around 65% of companies are fully compliant to norms.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] The Monetary Authority of Singapore is Singapore's central bank and financial regulatory authority.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] It administers the various statutes pertaining to money, banking, insurance, securities and the financial sector in general, as well as currency issuance.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] There is considerable regulation in the United Kingdom, some of which is derived from European Union legislation.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Various areas are policed by different bodies, such as the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA), Environment Agency, Scottish Environment Protection Agency, Information Commissioner's Office, Care Quality Commission, and others: see List of regulators in the United Kingdom.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Important compliance issues for all organizations large and small include the Data Protection Act 2018 and, for the public sector, Freedom of Information Act 2000.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Corporate scandals and breakdowns such as the Enron case of reputational risk in 2001 have increased calls for stronger compliance and regulations, particularly for publicly listed companies.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] The Office of Foreign Assets Control (OFAC) is an agency of the United States Department of the Treasury under the auspices of the Under Secretary of the Treasury for Terrorism and Financial Intelligence.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] OFAC administers and enforces economic and trade sanctions based on U.S. foreign policy and national security goals against targeted foreign states, organizations, and individuals.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Compliance in the U.S. generally means compliance with laws and regulations.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] These laws and regulations can have criminal or civil penalties.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] The definition of what constitutes an effective compliance plan has been elusive.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Most authors, however, continue to cite the guidance provided by the United States Sentencing Commission in Chapter 8 of the Federal Sentencing Guidelines.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Small Business Administration re-launched Business.gov (later Business.USA.gov and finally SBA.Gov) which provides a single point of access to government services and information that help businesses comply with government regulations.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Department of Labor, Occupational Health and Safety Administration (OSHA) was created by Congress to assure safe and healthful working conditions for working men and women by setting and enforcing standards and by providing training, outreach, education, and assistance.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] OSHA implements laws and regulations regularly in the following areas, construction, maritime, agriculture, and recordkeeping.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] The United States Department of Transportation also has various laws and regulations requiring that prime contractors when bidding on federally funded projects engage in good faith effort compliance, meaning they must document their outreach to certified disadvantaged business enterprises.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Data retention is a part of regulatory compliance that is proving to be a challenge in many instances.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] The security that comes from compliance with industry regulations can seem contrary to maintaining user privacy.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Data retention laws and regulations ask data owners and other service providers to retain extensive records of user activity beyond the time necessary for normal business operations.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] These requirements have been called into question by privacy rights advocates.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Compliance in this area is becoming very difficult.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Laws like the CAN-SPAM Act and Fair Credit Reporting Act in the U.S. require that businesses give people the right to be forgotten.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] In other words, they must remove individuals from marketing lists if it is requested, tell them when and why they might share personal information with a third party, or at least ask permission before sharing that data.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Now, with new laws coming out that demand longer data retention despite the individual’s desires, it can create some real difficulties.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Money laundering and terrorist financing pose significant threats to the integrity of the financial system and national security.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] To combat these threats, the EU has adopted a risk-based approach to Anti-Money Laundering and Combating the Financing of Terrorism (AML/CFT) that relies on cooperation and coordination between EU and national authorities.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] In this context, risk-based regulation refers to the approach of identifying and assessing potential risks of money laundering and terrorist financing and implementing regulatory measures proportional to those risks.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] However, the shared enforcement powers between EU and national authorities in the implementation and enforcement of AML/CFT regulations can create legal implications and challenges.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] The potential for inconsistent application of AML regulations across different jurisdictions can create regulatory arbitrage and undermine the effectiveness of AML efforts.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Additionally, a lack of clear and consistent legal frameworks defining the roles and responsibilities of EU and national authorities in AML enforcement can lead to situations where accountability is difficult to establish.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Corporate Governance Code (formerly the Combined Code) is issued by the Financial Reporting Council (FRC) and "sets standards of good practice in relation to board leadership and effectiveness, remuneration, accountability, and relations with shareholders".
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] All companies with a Premium Listing of equity shares in the U.K. are required under the Listing Rules to report on how they have applied the Combined Code in their annual report and accounts.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] It further demonstrates the relationship that subsists among shareholders, management, and the independent audit teams.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Financial statements must be prepared using a particular set of rules and regulations hence the rationale behind allowing the companies to apply the provisions of company law, international financial reporting standards (IFRS), as well as the U.K. stock exchange rules as directed by the FCA.
[src:soc2-compliance/regulatory-compliance] It is also possible that shareholders may not understand the figures as presented in the various financial statements, hence it is critical that the board should provide notes on accounting policies as well as other explanatory notes to help them understand the report better.
[src:soc2-compliance/system-and-organization-controls] The reports focus on controls grouped into five categories called *Trust Service Criteria*.
[src:soc2-compliance/system-and-organization-controls] The Trust Services Criteria were established by the AICPA through its Assurance Services Executive Committee (ASEC) in 2017 (2017 TSC).
[src:soc2-compliance/system-and-organization-controls] These control criteria are to be used by the practitioner/examiner (Certified Public Accountant, CPA) in attestation or consulting engagements to evaluate and report on controls of information systems offered as a service.
[src:soc2-compliance/system-and-organization-controls] The engagements can be done on an entity wide, subsidiary, division, operating unit, product line or functional area basis.
[src:soc2-compliance/system-and-organization-controls] The Trust Services Criteria were modeled in conformity to The Committee of Sponsoring Organizations of the Treadway Commission (COSO) *Internal Control – Integrated Framework* (COSO Framework).
[src:soc2-compliance/system-and-organization-controls] In addition, the Trust Services Criteria can be mapped to NIST SP 800 – 53 criteria and to EU General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) Articles.
[src:soc2-compliance/system-and-organization-controls] The AICPA auditing standard Statement on Standards for Attestation Engagements no.
[src:soc2-compliance/system-and-organization-controls] 18 (SSAE 18), section 320, "Reporting on an Examination of Controls at a Service Organization Relevant to User Entities' Internal Control Over Financial Reporting", defines two levels of reporting, type 1 and type 2.
[src:soc2-compliance/system-and-organization-controls] Additional AICPA guidance materials specify three types of reporting: SOC 1, SOC 2, and SOC 3.
[src:soc2-compliance/system-and-organization-controls] Trust Services Criteria were designed such that they can provide flexibility in application to better suit the unique controls implemented by an organization to address its unique risks and threats it faces.
[src:soc2-compliance/system-and-organization-controls] This is in contrast to other control frameworks that mandate specific controls whether applicable or not.
[src:soc2-compliance/system-and-organization-controls] Trust Services Criteria application in actual situations requires judgement as to suitability.
[src:soc2-compliance/system-and-organization-controls] The Trust Services Criteria are used when "evaluating the suitability of the design and operating effectiveness of controls relevant to the security, availability, processing integrity, confidentiality or privacy of information and systems used to provide product or services" – AICPA – ASEC.
[src:soc2-compliance/system-and-organization-controls] Organization of the Trust Services Criteria are aligned to the COSO framework's 17 principles with additional supplemental criteria organized into logical and physical access controls, system operations, change management and risk mitigation.
[src:soc2-compliance/system-and-organization-controls] Further, the additional supplemental criteria are shared among the Trust Services Criteria – Common Criteria (CC) and additional specific criteria for availability, processing integrity, confidentiality and privacy.
[src:soc2-compliance/system-and-organization-controls] Common criteria are labeled as, Control environment (CC1.x), Information and communication (CC2.x), Risk assessment (CC3.x), Monitoring of controls (CC4.x) and Control activities related to the design and implementation of controls (CC5.x).
[src:soc2-compliance/system-and-organization-controls] Common criteria are suitable and complete for evaluation security criteria.
[src:soc2-compliance/system-and-organization-controls] However, there additional category specific criteria for Availability (A.x), Processing integrity (PI.x), Confidentiality (C.x) and Privacy (P.x).
[src:soc2-compliance/system-and-organization-controls] Criteria for each trust services categories addressed in an engagement are considered complete when all criterial associated with that category are addressed.
[src:soc2-compliance/system-and-organization-controls] Availability – information and systems are available for operational use.
[src:soc2-compliance/system-and-organization-controls] Confidentiality – information is protected and available on a legitimate need to know basis.
[src:soc2-compliance/system-and-organization-controls] Applies to various types of sensitive information.
[src:soc2-compliance/system-and-organization-controls] Processing Integrity – system processing is complete, valid, accurate, timely and authorized.
[src:soc2-compliance/system-and-organization-controls] Privacy – personal information is collected, used, retained, disclosed and disposed according to policy.
[src:soc2-compliance/system-and-organization-controls] Privacy applies only to personal information.
[src:soc2-compliance/system-and-organization-controls] Additionally, there are specialized SOC reports for Cybersecurity and Supply Chain.
[src:soc2-compliance/system-and-organization-controls] SOC 1 and SOC 2 reports are intended for a limited audience – specifically, users with an adequate understanding of the system in question.
[src:soc2-compliance/system-and-organization-controls] SOC 3 reports contain less specific information and can be distributed to the general public.
[src:soc2-compliance/system-and-organization-controls] Only licensed CPA firms or audit firms certified to perform SOC assessments can conduct your SOC 2 audit.
[src:soc2-compliance/system-and-organization-controls] These auditors must be independent and adhere to AICPA standards.
[src:soc2-compliance/system-and-organization-controls] The SOC 2 Audit provides the organization's detailed internal controls report made in compliance with the five trust service criteria.
[src:soc2-compliance/system-and-organization-controls] It demonstrates how well the organization safeguards customer data and reassures customers that it provides services securely and reliably.
[src:soc2-compliance/system-and-organization-controls] SOC 2 reports are therefore intended to be made available only to customers and other stakeholders.
[src:soc2-compliance/system-and-organization-controls] A SOC 2 Readiness Assessment is a critical step before the audit.
[src:soc2-compliance/system-and-organization-controls] It helps identify gaps in controls, documentation, or evidence early, reducing surprises during the audit.
[src:soc2-compliance/system-and-organization-controls] Strong preparation includes completing documentation, validating system configurations, involving cross-functional teams, and ensuring continuous monitoring.
